Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of turnover tax in the Czech Republic and Germany
The foreword:
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the Court of Auditors has the power to audit all public finances.
The declaration calls for the Court of Auditors to have the power to examine tax collection as broadly as possible.
The organisation of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxation to be an important component of public revenue.
The main thematic focus of the 6th EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenues by the Court of Auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit work of an Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenues.
This is particularly true of taxes, the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies become increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which the national auditors can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the auditors of other countries.
Consider, for example, the audit of internationally organised fraud, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.
Court of Auditors auditing in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of the VAT and the MIAS system arose at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Court.
In the course of thorough preparation, the participating Court of Auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures for VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the evaluation of the available information, we made the selection of the examination objects for the examination planning.
Achieving consistent and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual Member States (in particular the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and increase transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only contribute to improving the work of the financial administration, but may also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international information exchange.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of turnover tax in the Czech Republic and Germany
An introduction to the game
File number: CZ) 06 / 27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject of examination:
(CZ) Management of VAT following the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(DE) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
Commission's audit target:
(CZ) The purpose of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the field of turnover tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter referred to as the "EC") with the free movement of goods and services, as well as the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
(DE) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on administrative assistance in the field of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations should be made to remedy them.
Based on an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006, the audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Court of Justice ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany.
The main areas of cooperation were the verification of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international administrative assistance between financial administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two countries.
A joint final report on the results of the audits has been prepared in accordance with European Guideline No 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards.
The period examined covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two Court of Auditors.
In addition to the focus on the exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004 of the Commission, other closely related aspects were examined, such as the registration of tax liabilities, tax returns and summary notices.
The examination also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for purposes of VAT.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the main criterion for registration is the violation of the VAT threshold laid down in the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, tax fleets receive only a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the tax filer receives a tax number valid only for domestic sales for purposes of VAT.
If the German taxpayer wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called USt-IdNr.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach is exempt from VAT, but is entitled to deduction of VAT.
In Germany, as far as the route passes through Germany, the transport service is subject to turnover tax.
Efforts should be made at EC level to harmonise the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover tax (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax authorities are only required to file VAT returns for tax periods of less than one year (month or quarter), tax authorities in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Pre-registrations of VAT and after the end of the calendar year a declaration of annual sales tax.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax preparers in Germany must submit VAT pre-registration electronically.
The introduction of the VAT electronic levy in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).
4) Summarized messages.
While tax preparers in the Czech Republic are required to file their Summary Notices with the Internal Revenue Service (FÄ), German tax preparers are required to file the Summary Notices with the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information contained in the Summary Notices will be available to the FÄ in the Czech Republic as soon as they are filed.
The data from the Summary Reports are only available to German FÄ only after their processing by the CLO.
Updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed to combat VAT fraud as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of Summary Notices would shorten the period between the time of the turnover and the update of the MIAS data.
This would allow for a timely assessment of taxation in the acquirer's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same time limits.
5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.
In the event of a request for information, the Czech CLO will monitor compliance with the three-month period.
The German CLO does not monitor processing times.
As a result, the German tax administration has dealt with a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the prescribed time limit.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended to the German CLO a permanent monitoring of the time limits (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful RMS criteria, elements or approaches must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
In the context of cooperation, the two Court of Auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed using CLO's legal options where there were doubts about correct taxation or suspected VAT fraud.
The Court of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the FÄ used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and re-established the VAT liability of the tax subject.
In these cases, the tax authorities had either unlawfully taken advantage of the VAT exemption or failed to declare the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FÄ could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used due to differences in legislation between the two Member States.
In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to provide the requested information.
A number of cases have been uncovered in which tax authorities have incorrectly reported turnover in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were correspondingly incorrect, so that the experts (the FÄ) had to determine in these cases (see 6).
The review process
