An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of CZK 1,000,000, shall be liable for payment on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has exceeded the threshold (§ 94 (1) of the Law Nr. 235 / 2004 Coll., concerning the VAT; hereinafter "Law Nr. 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
Current legislation does not allow for the retroactive registration of a taxable person who has exceeded the application deadline for registration.
An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic who provides services subject to turnover tax or services exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT must also be registered for VAT if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he fulfils other conditions set out in Law No. 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic who does not fulfil any of the conditions set out in the law may voluntarily apply for VAT registration.
The registration procedure under Law No 337 / 1992 commences with the receipt of the registration application by the local tax officer.
Those who wish to register voluntarily for VAT must specify in their application the date on which they apply for registration as a VAT subject.
The financial officer has to check the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all investments.
If he has doubts about the information contained therein, he shall ask the applicant to explain, supplement or substantiate the information provided.
Once the financial officer has verified that the trader meets the requirements for registration, he must issue a written communication on the registration and allocation of a tax number.
In the communication, the tax officer is required to indicate the date of entry into force of the VAT registration and the period of disposition for the VAT.
The investment period is the calendar quarter; unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the disposition period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover in the preceding calendar year has reached at least CZK 2,000,000 is entitled to choose the calendar month as the fixed period and has to inform the financial officer of this change.
The issue of a tax number in the registration decision always has a constitutive character.
The taxable person has to give the tax number in every communication (including payments) with the tax officer, and also in cases where a special law requires this (e.g. Law Nr. 235 / 2004 concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The tax number contains the encoding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification mark.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification mark, insofar as this is determined by a special law. In the case of legal persons, the general identification mark is the company identification number (in accordance with the provisions of § 33 (12) of Law No. 337 / 1992).
If the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his obligations despite the corresponding request by the financial officer, the local responsible financial officer shall register him as such.
A communication will also be issued, which will be sent to the taxman.
In the Czech Republic, every entrepreneur authorised to do business will receive a tax number at the time of his first registration for any type of tax.
This also applies to the registration as a VAT payer.
According to law No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-compliance with the obligation to register the VAT, the tax officer may require that the taxable person should have registered up to 10% of the proceeds from the taxable turnover that the person has unlawfully made without taxation for the period from the date on which the entrepreneur should have been registered as a taxable person, up to the date on which the registration as a taxable person was made by order of the tax officer (§ 98 (1) of the law Nr / 235).
The payment of this amount shall be deemed to be a tax payment within the meaning of § 98 (3) of Law Nr. 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements exist, the registration of a VAT subject can be deleted for two reasons:
1) There's no getting away from the fact that there's a lot of people out there who don't know what's going on.
Deletion of registration at the request of the taxable person, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
A tax preparer may request the deletion of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force mentioned in the registration notice.
2) Deletion of the registration of official acts (§ 106 (7) of Law Nr. 235 / 2004) if: a) the taxable person has not performed any service in the period of 12 consecutive months and has not informed the tax official of the reasons for it; b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations in accordance with Law Nr. 235 / 2004; c) the previous tax person no longer fulfils the requirements for the tax liaison.
B) Tax subject without legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic A person who is registered for tax purposes in another Member State and does not have a legal domicile, registered office or place of business in the Czech Republic, or a tax resident foreigner who performs services in the Czech Republic and has to file a tax return and pay taxes ("non-resident entrepreneur") in accordance with § 108 of Law Nr. 235 / 2004 for these services or deliveries shall be liable to pay tax on the provision of the services in question.
He must submit an application for registration with the FA Prague 1 at the latest on the day of the delivery in question.
In this application, he is obliged to indicate all the USt-IdNr. assigned to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than the date of the first tax-efficient provision of services in the Czech Republic, the FA Prague 1 has to register him retroactively as he became subject to turnover tax on the date of the first tax-efficient provision of services in the Czech Republic, in accordance with Law No. 235 / 2004.
In the event of a retroactive registration, FA Prague 1 shall require a document (invoices or written explanations) from the contractors concerned to provide proof of performance.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration in the Czech Republic before performing a service for the first time, FA Prague 1 shall require the submission of the contractual documents justifying the performance.
As of 31 December 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with the FA Prague 1, of which 124 were from Germany. As of 31 December 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, of which 233 were from Germany.
According to the provisions of § 106 (9) of Law Nr. 235 / 2004, the tax officer is authorized to delete the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur as of 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to file tax declarations or tax returns and to pay taxes.
During the examination of the NKÚ, it turned out that in the case of the filing of a tax return by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. in accordance with the mandatory deadline for filing a tax return, this declaration had not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant to the possibility of deletion of registration, become known to the FA later than 31 January, it is no longer possible to cancel the registration of the non-resident entrepreneur for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of tax preparers in Germany
Pursuant to the provisions of the Ordinance on Taxation (§ § 137, 138 AO), any business operation must be notified to the municipality and / or the competent tax office.
This notification must be made no later than one month after the start of business.
The municipality will forward the application to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office determines that a business activity has commenced but has not been notified, it may also register the tax lien retroactively.
Regardless of whether they are resident or not, tax evaders in Germany are required to register for VAT on Zwekke if they meet the requirements of § 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the level of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Special FÄ are responsible for entrepreneurs residing abroad.
For example, FA ChemnitzSüd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who have their registered office in the Czech Republic.
As of 30 April 2004, 295 Czech entrepreneurs had been registered with this company; as of 1 March 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs had been registered there.
According to the findings of the BRH, these special jurisdictions frequently refused to register so-called bogus self-employed persons residing in the new or Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted after the accession of these ten countries to the Community, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own businesses.
These self-employed persons do not fulfil the conditions laid down in § 2 UStG for recognition as entrepreneurs, as they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the way in which they carry out their work.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must complete a questionnaire drawn up by the competent FA and provide information on the company and the activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a mandatory form for all German universities.
It is processed either in special organizational units within the FÄ or in the organizational units generally responsible for the tax planning.
With the help of this preprint, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual tax subject before the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the competent FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identification feature for the controller, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries, he needs a USt-IdNr.
This is assigned by the CLO on request, if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for sales tax purposes.
The USt-IdNr. is automatically assigned by the CLO if the taxable person declares intra-Community deliveries in his or her VAT declarations or in his or her annual declaration of VAT.
The USt-IdNr. is composed of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. when he ceases to do business), but only after the completion of all tax transactions (predisposition of all financial years) or 2. If the tax administration determines that he is no longer running a business.
As a rule, the validity of the USt-IdNr. depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In such cases, the FÄ must inform the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number so that the validity of the VAT ID can be terminated at that time.
According to the German Sales Tax Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax fleets do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting value added tax has not exceeded the amount of €17,500 and 2. is unlikely to exceed the amount of €50,000 in the following year.
The so-called small entrepreneurs are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small business owners are required to register with the tax office and file an annual sales tax return.
A small businessman can explain the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the following five years.
He may then invoke the VAT and deduct the pre-tax.
Non-resident taxpayers may appoint a Fiscal Representative (§ 22a UStG).
A precondition for this is that they only make tax-free sales and waive the deduction.
The fiscal representative fulfills the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for the purposes of the VAT.
The accounts indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two countries is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold amount specified in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but due to different organisational structures in the different federal states, differences can occur.
In the Czech Republic, the taxable person receives a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the case of its registration for the VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically request the allocation of a USt-IdNr..
Both NKÚ and BRH found that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which grants a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community transactions, can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-stage system allows retroactive (national) registration in cases where the taxman does not register his business activities with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows a valid predisposition to the value added tax for previous investment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the VAT debt.
As the different registration procedures cause problems, the rules should be harmonised across the EC.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office of Taxation to each natural person after birth.
This number is valid for natural persons resident in Germany for life.
When a natural person commits a business activity, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as the USt-IdNr..
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a tax subject and the allocation of the USt-IdNr..
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the administration of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
The legal regulations in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of § 70 of Law No. 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004 the carriage of passengers between the individual Member States as well as between the Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic is exempt from VAT and is entitled to deduction of VAT.
The exemption from VAT also applies if the transport of persons who are registered as tax subject in other Member States or foreigners who are tax subject in their own country is carried out.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport procedure.
If non-resident entrepreneurs do not carry out any economic activity in the Czech Republic other than cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach, they are not obliged to register as taxable entities in the Czech Republic.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport has been exempted from VAT in accordance with the Act on the Accession of the Czech Republic Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b), which states in the text:
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, the Czech Republic may, pursuant to point 17 in Annex F of the Directive, maintain the exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the conditions of Article 28 (4) of the Directive are met or until the same exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
Pursuant to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as transposed in Germany by § 3b (1) UStG, a carriage service shall be carried out where the carriage is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is taxable in Germany.
Nor does German taxation distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxable person is transported through Germany, the part of the carriage which is attributable to Germany is deemed to be taxable.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must notify his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
This registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each motor bus mentioned in the registration of the tax subject.
The entrepreneur must state his taxable transport services in a German VAT declaration.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the Chemnitz-Süd FA.
If the transport service is provided for a domestically resident entrepreneur, the non-resident taxpayer does not have to pay the VAT himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic customer of the services has to pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount invoiced to the non-resident taxpayer. This process is called the "transfer of tax liability" and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax preparer and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax return with regard to taxable passenger transportation:
Customs mobile control groups check the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups submit an inspection report to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxpayer may deduct the VAT paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT declaration, it may order an audit to be carried out in the FA or use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see no. 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxable person refuses to pay the legally established value added tax, the FA may request administrative assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters for the verification of the VAT declaration or the compliance with the tax law by a non-resident bus operator to be too burdensome in relation to the low income from the VAT on taxable passenger transport.
In particular, auditing the books of a non-resident tax preparer causes disproportionately high costs for the tax preparer himself and for the tax administration.
The latter must check the foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language but also of the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, in the case of such an examination, a higher amount of time is to be expected than in the case of a resident tax inspector, although the examination is limited to the passenger transport carried out in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national tax administration, but also those of the other Member States, insofar as he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which even a single passenger transport is carried out, the taxing entity must comply with all existing tax legislation in the various languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
Thus, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two countries.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States as well as between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Czech Republic's Act of Accession to the EC.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to turnover tax in accordance with the route of carriage which falls within German territory.
If a non-resident taxpayer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify this to the competent FA in advance.
This registers the taxable person who has to declare the taxable part of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax fleets registered with the Chemnitz-South FA have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The amount of tax involved is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
The Member States which levy VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common VAT system have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax burden.
In order to avoid the disproportionate costs of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be taxable in one Member State.
This could be the state in which the carriage begins or where the service provider is resident.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales tax returns
Taxation and processing of VAT declarations in the Czech Republic
Insofar as the law does not stipulate otherwise, the entrepreneur, even if no tax liability has arisen, is obliged to file a VAT return on the pre-print provided by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period.
The tax liability arises with the expiry of the deadline for submitting the VAT declaration. According to Law No. 235 / 2004, the VAT on the import of goods is excluded from this regulation. Here, the due date of the tax is determined according to the customs regulations.
In the event of a refund claim resulting from higher than average deductible taxes, this amount will be refunded to the taxable person within 30 days of the determination of this deduction, without the need for an application.
The time limit shall not be applied in cases in which the tax officer initiates a tax procedure concerning the tax liability of the taxable person.
Pursuant to § 73 (11) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the right to deduction may be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the claim to deduction of deduction arose.
After the expiry of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the period in which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary tax return.
An amendment to Law No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the submission of a supplementary VAT declaration only for the period during which the right to deduction of VAT could have been claimed for the first time.
A tax litigant must file a supplementary VAT declaration if: a) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax liability, b) he makes corrections by which the last known tax liability is not changed, but only previous information is changed, c) he makes corrections to the VAT rate and the tax debt in accordance with § 49 of Law No. 235 / 2004.
A tax preparer may file a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The taxpayer must file the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts in question were established.
Revenue tax returns can be filed electronically either via the Internet or via data carriers.
The delivery via Internet can be made with or without a certified electronic signature.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted on a medium.
The preprint for the VAT declaration contains separate lines for indicating the value of intra-Community supplies and purchases.
The value of related services must be stated in separate lines of the VAT declaration.
Some headings are used for automated primary controls within the framework of the ATIS system.
The value of the goods delivered to other EC Member States to persons registered there as taxable will be compared with the data provided by the Czech tax authorities in their Summary Notices.
The value of purchases of goods from other Member States by persons registered as taxable persons is compared by means of the MIAS with the information contained in the Summary Statements of tax fleets from other EC Member States.
Within the framework of the ATIS system, a credibility check of VAT returns is carried out by the FA.
This is done automatically, as the VAT declaration cannot be processed without the prior examination.
The credibility test involves a calculation of the measures of credibility and an assessment of the risks of VAT returns.
According to the provisions of § 37 (1) of Law Nr. 337 / 1992, the FA may repeatedly impose a fine of up to CZK 2 million on persons who do not comply with their non-monetary obligations under this or a special tax law or a decision under this law.
Automated tax information system - Automated tax information system used by Czech tax offices for technical support of tax collection.
