Tax and processing of VAT declarations in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registrations and the annual VAT declaration.
Those tax preparers who are required to file VAT pre-registrations must nevertheless file an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not required to pay VAT must file an annual VAT return.
The taxable persons are generally obliged to make a VAT pre-registration (§ 18 (2) UStG) until 10 days after the end of the calendar quarter in which the VAT is generated.
However, if the VAT liability is more than €6,136 in the previous year or if the company is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obligated to make monthly VAT pre-registrations at the latest up to 10 days after the expiry of the relevant month.
The taxable person can also opt for the submission of monthly VAT pre-registrations if he received a refund of more than €6,136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual sales tax is not more than €512, neither VAT pre-registrations nor VAT declarations are required.
Any resulting VAT liability shall be paid 10 days after the expiry of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
(Legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the reimbursement of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security for the refund amount can be offered.
In principle, VAT declarations, including reimbursement cases, must be processed quickly.
The German sales tax law allows an extension of these (delivery or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT pre-registration and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. However, in the case of monthly notifications, a special advance payment is to be made.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability established for the pre-notification period of December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT pre-registration.
There is no "supplementary" VAT declaration.
Once the VAT declaration to be filed by 31 May of the following year has been filed with the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT declaration, but only the incorrect annual VAT declaration.
Corrections of this VAT declaration to the advantage or disadvantage of the taxable person are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT declaration was filed.
After the expiry of this four-year period, a VAT declaration can normally only be corrected in cases of light-hearted tax reduction or tax evasion.
Taxpayers must submit VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The FÄ may grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid unfavourable hardship.
The annual VAT declaration can be made either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the delivery is made without certification, the tax administrator must also make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no VAT pre-registrations or declarations are made, the tax administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the taxable person 6.
In case of a late levy, the taxable person may be subject to a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to an amount of €25,000).
In an earlier investigation, the BRH found that the FÄ often do not levy this late surcharge.
In cases where the FÄ levied the late fees, the amount was set in an uneven and arbitrary manner.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, in particular when submitting the annual VAT return.
The preprint of the VAT declaration contains separate lines for value indications for intra-Community deliveries or purchases.
There are also separate lines for the provision of services.
Non-taxable sales are to be indicated in a separate line of the VAT declaration.
The VAT returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated personnel.
The data of electronically filed tax returns are immediately available to the tax administration.
