Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax preparers must file their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the end of the tax period.
Depending on the turnover of the taxable person, the taxable period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
Depending on the amount of their tax liability of the previous year, tax filers in Germany have to file their prior filings at the latest 10 days after either the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
The annual declaration of VAT must be made by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The ability to file an annual VAT declaration has a number of advantages and disadvantages:
+ After the end of the calendar year, the tax administrator may correct the errors in the monthly pre-registrations by submitting a single VAT return;
- if the taxable person corrects his or her information on intra-Community transactions, the correction cannot be attributed to a specific reporting period of the ICM;
- The Länder do not collect MIAS data on intra-Community acquisitions of German tax preparers until the annual VAT declarations have usually been processed.
