In contrast to the current regulations in the Czech Republic, German tax authorities are obliged to issue the VAT pre-registration electronically.
The introduction of the electronic filing of tax returns in the Czech Republic would increase the effectiveness of the Czech tax administration.
A summary of the reports
Presentation and processing of summary notices in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of § 102 of the Law No. 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur who supplies goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes is obliged to make such summary reports (hereinafter referred to as "ZM").
The value of the goods delivered shall always be stated in Czech currency in accordance with the USt-IdNr7, the individual tax brackets under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information about services is not provided in the ZM.
Taxpayers with a calendar monthly or quarterly tax period must submit the ZM to the local competent FA no later than the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in a correction TIM within 15 days of the error being identified.
Faulty data in the ZM will always be replaced by data from the correction ZM.
Similar to tax returns, tax filers can also file their returns electronically.
In the event that a tax officer does not provide a CM or a correction CZK, even though he is required to do so in accordance with Law Nr. 235 / 2004, the financial officer shall ask him to hand over the relevant CZM, pointing out the consequences of the non-payment. In the event of non-fulfilment of non-monetary obligations, the financial officer shall be authorised to impose repeated fines of up to CZK 2 million in accordance with § 37 of Law Nr. 337 / 1992.
The NKÚ found in its investigation that the FÄ mostly did not use its power to impose fines on defaulting tax evaders.
In particular, the tax faculty are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations, as the failure to pay the ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT debt.
Pursuant to § 102 (5) of Law Nr. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is obliged to check the information in the ZM or Correction ZM, to remove any ambiguity and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
