- the financial officer has proved the inaccuracy of the information reported by the taxable person in the ZM or Correction ZM.
Corrections entered by the tax officer, without a correction ZM having been issued by the taxable person, do not replace the platitude of the taxable person to submit a correction ZM, but only lead to the correction of the data in the MIAS, so that they are up to date, complete and accurate.
The data from the ICs will be forwarded to the Member States concerned.
Only the national tax authority, designated for cooperation with the other Member States in the field of VAT, is allowed to transmit and receive this data.
This is the CLO (in the Czech Republic, this function is carried out by the Department of International Mutual Assistance in the field of VAT in the Ministry of Finance) and the message "O _ MCTL" is automatically sent to the CLO from the other Member States.
It contains all incorrect USt-IdNr., which were specified in the transmitted ZM lines.
If the incorrect USt-IdNr. is used in some of the transmitted lines of the ZM or the corrected ZM, an entry is made in the list of the wrong USt-IdNr.
The list contains a "message about doubts regarding USt-IdNr."
The financial officer checks the data and enters the result of the check into the system.
When purchasing goods from another Member State, the taxable person must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the lines of the VAT return intended for this purpose.
The CLO will forward selected cases of differences between the value of the purchases made by the Czech taxable person in his VAT return and the value of the goods delivered by the supplier from the other Member State in his ZM to the competent FA for examination.
The experts there must investigate the discrepancies.
Three different situations can then occur:
a) The value specified by the Czech acquirer in the relevant headings of its VAT return is lower than the value of the supplies supplied by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the accuracy of the information.
b) The difference is zero.
This situation can result either from a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects his VAT return) or from a change in the information in the VAT return (the Czech tax preparer in the meantime issues a supplementary VAT declaration on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the tax officer to verify the accuracy of the information in the VAT return.
c) The value of the goods purchased from other Member States, which the Czech taxable person has indicated in his VAT return, is higher than the value of the goods delivered by the suppliers of the other EC Member States.
Again, it is at the discretion of the financial officer to check the accuracy of the information.
After verifying the differences and clarifying the reasons for their appearance, the financial officer enters the results of his review into ATIS.
These results will be forwarded to the CLO.
