Presentation and processing of the summary reports in Germany
Entrepreneurs who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or who participate in triangular transactions must submit quarterly reports listing intra-Community deliveries by acquirer (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The tender must be made no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter in question.
If a long-term extension is granted for the submission of VAT declarations, this shall also apply to the ZM.
The ZM shall be submitted to the CLO.
The electronic levy has been in effect since 1 January 2007.
The competent FA may allow exemptions for individual tax areas in order to avoid unfavourable hardship.
If the controller determines that the ZM was faulty, he is required to submit a correction ZM within one month.
In the case of non-submission of the CZM, the CLO initiates an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first reminder - second reminder, coupled with the threat of a penalty and - fixing the penalty.
Although the German tax code allows the imposition of a penalty payment of up to €25,000 (§ 329 AO), the CLO imposes penalties of €125, 250 and 500 in three stages.
In addition, § 26a (1) Nr. 5 UStG stipulates that the controller acts improperly, if he intentionally or recklessly issues a ZM not correctly, not completely or not in time, or if he does not correct a ZM or does not correct it in time.
This infringement can be punishable by a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered by the FÄ into the MIAS, because the processing of the ZM is the exclusive responsibility of the CLO.
The data of the ZM are stored only at the CLO.
The information from the summary reports is only available to the FÄ after processing by the CLO.
The time limits for processing CCGs are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.
The data of the ZM must be stored within three months of the relevant calendar quarter (in MIAS).
In case of incorrect USt-IdNr. in the ZM of German tax preparers, the German CLO will receive a message "O _ MCTL" from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the right data.
If the CLO does not manage to obtain the correct information, the case will be referred to the relevant FA.
It is then up to them to request the correct information.
In the course of its examination, the BRH found that most entrepreneurs corrected the USt-IdNr. at the request of the CLO.
However, the reminder, as well as the threat and imposition of up to three consecutive fines, takes too much time when a tax evader may be involved in cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases that were finally reported to the competent FÄ were usually closed within one to two months.
The competent FA refused to grant tax exemption for the notified intra-Community supplies in 73% of these forgeries.
If the controller provided the correct USt-IdNr., the FA asked him to submit a corrected ZM to the CLO, because the FÄ cannot correct the MIAS data itself.
The BRH found that neither the FÄ nor the CLO controlled the release of the corrected ZM.
Therefore, the tax authorities often did not comply with the request. Since the CLO does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, there is no comparison of the data on goods deliveries made in the VAT declarations or the VAT declaration with the corresponding data in the ZM before these data are sent to the CLO of the other Member States.
This comparison can only be made by the FÄ. This is usually done during the preparation of a special VAT audit.
Data received from other Member States will be processed by CLO.
Incorrect USt-IdN are detected and reported to the Member States concerned.
The data will be used for the control of income tax in the Member States.
As soon as they are available in the system, the CLO compares with data from previous calendar quarters.
