This happens continuously, whereas an auction of the acquisition data of all sales tax fleets is later compiled and forwarded to the FÄ.
The risk management system (RMS) for the investment process then compares this data with those for intra-Community acquisitions.
The system fully verifies (only) those entrepreneurs who are not fully entitled to deduct the deduction.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax preparers who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State are required to submit a CZM to the local competent FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FÄ process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
The values of the intra-Community deliveries notified by the tax authorities in the ZM shall be compared at the FÄ with the values of intra-Community deliveries specified by the same tax authorities in their VAT declarations.
The results of the reconciliation will be taken into account in the tax setting process.
In Germany, tax preparers who have made intra-Community deliveries are required to file quarterly returns within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter.
Since 1 January 2007, tax inspectors have to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM are only available to the FÄ after processing by the CLO.
Both in the Czech Republic and in Germany, the tax authorities in the ZM state only the delivery of goods.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. In contrast to the Czech FÄ, the German FÄ cannot itself correct incorrect information in individual lines of the given ZM.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect USt-IdNr. was not corrected even if the correct USt-IdNr. was communicated to the FA by the controller.
The German tax administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries provided by German tax authorities in their VAT pre-registrations with the information provided by the corresponding ZM.
Differences between the pre-registration data and the ZM are not regularly disclosed until the German CLO transmits the MIAS data to other Member States.
Based on these findings of the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the transmitted MIAS data.
Data on goods delivered by other Member States to Czech tax authorities will be compared in the Czech Republic with data on purchases of goods stated by Czech tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO makes the comparison for each calendar quarter separately.
The most serious cases of deviations are forwarded to the FÄ for examination.
Unlike the Czech tax administration, the German tax administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such a general control will only be carried out in the case of tax evaders who are not fully entitled to deduct the deduction.
In addition, the German tax administration controls the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions of other tax entities only if the RMS produces a test reference or if the tax subject has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves the FÄ of the need to clarify the reasons for any differences.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community purchases must be available as early as possible.
The current system of CCNs, in particular MIAS, provides information to the financial authorities that may well be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax fleets had to submit monthly ZM.
The monthly levy would only insignificantly increase the bureaucratic burden, as most tax evaders in the Czech Republic and Germany are already required to file monthly VAT returns or pre-registrations and no more information is required for the ZM than for VAT returns or advance declarations.
In order to avoid red tape, the ZM levy could be combined with the levy of VAT returns and / or advance declarations.
However, a shift to the monthly levy of SDRs would cause more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community supplies and those on intra-Community purchases and would increase the flow of data between CLO.
In 2006, the German government considered the general introduction of monthly SDRs.
The implementation failed because of the objections of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly forwarding of MIAS data to the CLO of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the concentration on the monthly levy to be effective, it is necessary to agree on the single monthly levy at European level, so that it is possible to update the MIAS data monthly.
