International exchange of information at level 3
Implementation of international information exchange in the Czech Republic
The international exchange of information makes it possible for tax officials to obtain information from other Member States on intra-Community transactions and on the tax transactions that they have carried out.
Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on mutual assistance in the field of VAT repealing Directive (EEC) No 218 / 92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003)") distinguishes between two basic types of exchange of information: exchange of information on request and spontaneous exchange of information (without prior request).
The international exchange of information on request is carried out by means of a request for information (RFI) using the standardized SCAC form.
The financial officials in the Czech Republic send their RFI or their responses to an RFI received by the Finance Directorate to the CLO. The CLO is responsible for translating the information provided in the standardized SCAC form into the foreign language and forwarding it to the other Member States.
In addition, CLO receives requests for information (RFI) from other Member States and replies to requests sent. It ensures their translation into Czech and their distribution to the competent FÄ for processing.
Art. 8 of Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 sets a maximum period of three months from receipt of the request for its processing.
All RFIs exchanged between the Czech Republic and Germany during the tested period have been audited by NKÚ.
Out of the total number of 94 RFIs received from Germany, 70 cases (i.e. 74,5%) were dealt with within the three-month period; a further 23 cases (i.e. 24.5%) exceeded this time limit.
In the remaining one case, no reply had been sent to Germany until the NKÚ had examined it. More detailed information on the time limits within which requests made by Germany were answered by the Czech Republic can be found in Figure 2.
The total number of 335 requests for information (RFI) sent from the Czech Republic to Germany resulted in 136 responses (i.e. 40.6%) within the three-month period; a further 179 (i.e. 53.4%) were processed after this period and in 19 cases no reply had yet been received from Germany (in the remaining one case, due to the stated information, it was not possible to determine when Germany had replied to the request for information).
