The international exchange of information without prior request takes place either automatically, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Information relevant to the determination of VAT liability is often transmitted to tax officials in other Member States without prior request.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected by the CLO.
The exchange of information between the various Member States will take place electronically.
"Automatic exchange" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 means the systematic transmission of previously established information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals without prior request.
"Structured automatic exchange" means the systematic transmission of previously established information to another Member State without prior request, as soon as the relevant information is available.
The Czech Republic informs the other Member States in the automatic exchange of information on deliveries of new vehicles.
This information is obtained by the financial officer from the form reporting the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with § 19 of the Law No. 235 / 2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer will enter the required data in the relevant document and forward it directly to the responsible employee of the Financial Directorate, where this data will be collected and sent to the CLO for further processing. After that, the data will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified time limit, namely within two months at the latest after the end of the quarter in which it was obtained.
The Czech Republic will also provide other Member States with information on mail order transactions that are tax-free in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions that appear to be inadmissible and on potential missing traders.
This information will be transmitted to the other Member States by means of an SCAC imprint in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information originates from the local competent FA.
The FÄ send the completed preprint SCAC 2004 by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which forwards the SCACpreprints to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the used SCACprint is one-page.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the BRH were sent in order to ensure the taxation of profits in the other Member State or to demonstrate the tax-free status of intra-Community supplies from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it checks whether the value of the supplies referred to in the request exceeds the minimum limit of €15,000.
If there is no adequate justification for the request, the German CLO refuses to provide information regarding a turnover that is below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO provides the translation of the freely worded texts in the SCAC preprint [(B1-17) or (E), if they are not written in either German or English.
In order to respond to the request for information, the CLO shall forward it to the competent FA, referring to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of the German treasury.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor compliance with the deadline, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FÄ to respond to unfinished requests for information.
The FÄ receive the necessary information by writing a letter from the controller or carrying out an external inspection.
The external auditors usually choose between two forms of audit: the special VAT audit, which covers all tax-related transactions over a period of several months, or the so-called VAT review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
In this short and ﬂexible form of examination, an announcement to the tax inspector is not necessary and it has proved its worth in the examination of a single transaction.
With regard to the automatic exchange of information, Germany shall provide the following information to the other Member State: - on USt-IdNr., which have been allocated to undertakings established in other EC Member States, - on the reimbursement of pre-tax payments to entrepreneurs established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has committed itself to providing the following information to the other EC Member States in the framework of the structured automatic exchange of information:
a. The supply of new vehicles to entrepreneurs without VAT, b. Distance sales (mail order) to other EC Member States which are not subject to VAT in Germany, c. Significant differences between the purchases reported by a taxable person and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community deliveries of goods which have been incorrectly subject to taxation in Germany by the tax authorities. Potential "Missing Traders" who have made intra-Community sales, regardless of whether their UI number is still valid or has already been deleted, as well as tax evaders who have made intra-Community deliveries to the USD or misuse of a number.
Comparison and evaluation
The request for information or spontaneous information is sent both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local competent FÄ, who send the appropriate SCACPrinters to the CLO.
While the Czech CLO uses bilingual SCACPrinters (Czech-English) and translates information given into English or German, the German FÄ follow the instruction to write requests for information or spontaneous requests on a one-language form only in German.
The German CLO does not make translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany between 1 May 2004 and 31 December 2005, NKÚ found that 74.5% of requests for information received were dealt with by the Czech tax administration within the three-month period, while requests for information sent to Germany were dealt with by the German tax administration in 40.6% of cases within that period.
Although the German CLO refers the FÄ to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of reminders, a high proportion of requests for information that have been answered for a limited period of time occur.
For this reason, the BRH has recommended a continuous reminder procedure to the German CLO.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German CLO is now reminding the tax offices to reply to the outstanding requests for information.
Sales tax risk management
Risk Management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organisational units at different levels of financial management are involved in risk management in the field of turnover tax.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organisational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Department of Methodology and Economic Administration of the VAT or its Risk Management Unit deals with the identification of potential risk areas for the tax revenue and evaluates the trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At national level, this body coordinates the requirements for the "credibility of VAT returns" criterion and uses the MIAS data to detect possible tax evasion in the context of intra-Community supplies and purchases.
Based on data on the Czech Republic's trade balance, it evaluates high-risk goods, prepares the concept of risk management in the area of VAT and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and other Member States.
The department for international administrative assistance in the field of VAT provides inter alia for the exchange of information, participates in the creation and creation of a relevant information database, evaluates the data available from other Member States in the MIAS system, carries out publicity work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003.
