The Tax Audit and Investigation Unit carries out risk analyses in the context of the methodological management of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, produces risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from the tax administration and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigators exist in the financial directorates. Their tasks include the search for tax subject areas and sectors which are high-risk in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. Internet transactions, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered tax subject (e.g. in the sectors of Internet services, job placement, electronic and print media, etc.), the investigation of links in cases of chain fraud and the provision of information to the local tax authorities.
Special examination units have been set up in 12 selected subjects.
These have a regional competence and, with the appropriate authorisation, carry out tax audits outside the local jurisdiction of the FÄ.
The need to set up special audit units resulted from the increase in detected new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly linked to chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of tax investigators or concentrate on tax fugitives with specific activities, multinational companies and tax fugitives with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the field of VAT have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk-bearing nature of tax returns, - the task of "selection of the tax areas to be examined," whereby the tax areas to be examined are selected on the basis of certain criteria - the task of "MIAS," which enables tax officials to access data provided by the other EC Member States.
The task "MIAS" enables inter alia: - verification of the validity of the USt-IdNr. of tax fleets from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech taxable person, as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the tax plane in question from other Member States, - creation of a list of tax fleets who have not submitted ZM - formal control of the information provided by tax authorities in the Czech Republic in their ZM before these data are transmitted to other Member States - preparation of a list of tax fledgling persons whose VAT returns and other goods delivered to other Member States do not correspond to the value of all the goods purchased by ZM in the other Member States, and whose VAT declarations from the other Member States do not correspond to the ZM with the value of all the goods purchased in the other Member States.
As part of their mission to combat tax evasion, tax officials have access to data from public authorities such as commercial registers, land registers, motor vehicle registers, commercial registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 Submission and processing of the Summary Notices in the Czech Republic.
Risk Management in Germany
Because of its federal structure, both the federal ﬁnance authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 Länder are involved in the development and implementation of an RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
While there are joint development working groups, neither the CLO nor the federal tax administrations have a fully unified set of data.
At the level of the CLO, the unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as "KUSS" - Coordination Centre for VAT Special Examinations and Tax Investigations) collects the audit findings on fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER has been set up at the KUSS. There, the tax offices can enter and query the names of discovered missing traders or VAT fraudsters.
The KUSS coordinates related cases of VAT fraud at national level as well as cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the KUSS is incorporated into the development of the RMS through its participation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other CLO and BMF organisational units are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of other Member States' UICC No., which appear in the ZM German Tax Issues, will be carried out by the CLO.
This formal review takes place prior to the transmission of the ICM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its benefits (s. 4.4.2).
Examination of the validity of USt-IdNr. referred to in the SDM is carried out on the basis of O _ MCTL identifications transmitted by the other Member States (see also 4.4.2 for the procedure for rectifying invalid USt-IdNr.).
In addition, the CLO's RMS is based on MIAS data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of communications for the detection of suspected missing traders. Certain characteristics are used as clues, which usually occur in carousel transactions.
The FÄ of the federal states are instructed to process these communications and to forward the results of their investigations in certain cases to the CLO.
The BRH audit confirmed that all available features must be included in order to give a sufficient probability of concluding a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended to the BMF to work with combinations of different clues in the preparation of the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other factors, such as the payment behaviour of the taxman, the economic sector or the company's shareholding.
A second level of risk management exists in the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT pre-registrations and annual declarations.
For example, the system draws up a list of those tax fleets who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT pre-registration or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the CLO for monitoring of the complete submission of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the acquisitions specified by the taxable person in his annual VAT return are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The tax administrations of the Länder avoid comparing the quarterly data, as this would result in too many discrepancies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud, such as:
- suppliers and acquirers assume different dates for the execution of intra-Community sales;
- different accounting and tax declaration of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms that are based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, age of owners / shareholders, number of employees and method of payment of the tax lien).
Bavaria has introduced a rules-based risk management system that allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter "risk managers") to program their own rules to identify suspected tax fraudsters.
This system finds the FÄ use when processing the VAT advance reports.
This means that the competent FA receives the information of the RMS before the value added tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, the risk managers must adapt the rules according to the feedback from the FÄ.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of uncovered back-up cases.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system draws up a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FÄ decide on the examination of the tax subject.
After the audit, the auditors will have to report their findings so that RMS can learn from the results of the audits it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rules-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed sales tax returns and some other clues, this Neuro-Fuzzy system (also called the Datamining System) calculates how likely it is that a tax preparer is involved in tax fraud.
It then creates a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
Based on this list, the FÄ select the relevant controllers for testing and report the test results to the relevant data center.
The introduction of these three RMS is under way in the Länder.
As each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three systems for combating fraud appears to be effective.
It remains to be seen whether the hoped-for effects will materialize during actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three above-mentioned German Länder, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has proved to be a European problem, not a national one.
Those involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one Member State, but in several.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this does not happen, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by European-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is established.
Any other Member State involved in fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be a European exchange of experience on RMS.
