With the German answer to this request, three invoices were sent which showed a total value of the delivered goods of €31,999, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech tax authorities and the MIAS data.
By means of a request to the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ found that after receiving the reply from Germany, he had contacted the accountant of the Czech Tax Office and stayed with her in such a way that, after checking the invoices, she and the company owner wanted to discuss the issue of a supplementary VAT declaration for the third quarter of 2004.
So far, no supplementary VAT declaration has been issued.
The Czech tax official informed NKÚ that he would proceed in such a way that the deadlines for retroactive VAT fixing for the relevant tax period would be respected.
17.
In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax authorities delivered goods worth €11,600 to the German tax authorities.
In the context of the intergovernmental exchange of information, the German tax official asked for verification whether the so-called Czech tax fugitive actually existed, since the alleged capital owner of the German tax fugitive had established a number of phantom ﬁrms in Germany.
In the course of the FA's review of the transaction, the Czech tax inspector confirmed the purchase of the goods.
According to the Czech tax authorities, however, the goods were not delivered from Germany to the Czech Republic, but were resold in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax inspector presented evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech taxable person was not registered in Germany as subject to turnover tax and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question either in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany and the Czech tax official sent this information to the German tax administration in his reply to the request for information.
By means of a request to the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax inspector had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004, in which he, among other things, declared the value of the goods he had acquired from a German tax collector and, at the same time, asserted the right of deduction for the purchase from other Member States.
In his Czech VAT declaration he declared no VAT on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration issued after the external audit, the Czech tax official fixed the VAT debt unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, in this case there was no acquisition of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
Thus, the Czech finance official drew the wrong conclusion in the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German tax official corrected the tax return of the German tax authority and demanded the payment of €1,600 in VAT.
In addition, the competent FA sent a control communication to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
In the following cases, operators declared intra-Community deliveries which may not have been carried out:
18.
The Czech tax official received a request for information from the German tax administration on the question of whether the Czech tax inspector had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German tax inspector in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied by a copy of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech tax inspector.
A photocopy of the passport of the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle was also included.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech tax official found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic, and that he had no contacts with a German tax collector.
The VAT registration certificate, the imprint of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech tax administration.
With this information the Czech tax official answered the request for information and at the same time stated that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
By means of a request to the local Czech tax official, the NKÚ established that the Czech tax office is not located at the address indicated in the commercial register and that the managing director of the company is unreachable.
After a tax appeal procedure for the February 2005 tax period, the Czech tax official fixed the tax liability of the Czech tax lien at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an Internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local competent German tax official had rejected the claim of the German tax inspector for exemption from the VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the VAT declaration and the reported values from other Member States.
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a Czech tax preparer was supposed to have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax preparer.
As the acquisition declared by the German tax authorities did not correspond to the MIAS data, the German tax official requested the verification of the supplies and payment of the supplies within the framework of the interstate exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech tax official stated that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumably a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax inspector issued a VAT declaration and a ZM, which had been signed by an unauthorised person, namely that shareholder of the company, after the deletion of the managing director in the commercial register.
The accountant of the Czech tax office informed the tax official that the capital owner had deposited the payment received for the goods in euros into the company's account.
Cash receipts were not issued.
By request to the local Czech FA, the NKÚ found that the tax official had recognised the Czech tax authority's claim for VAT exemption on goods delivered to other Member States worth CZK 1.326.307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1.416.180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German tax official did not correct the VAT declaration of the German acquirer, as a German court had meanwhile confirmed the insolvency of the German tax litigant.
As the previous external audit had shown no evidence of tax fraud, there was no prospect of being able to collect a fixed VAT liability.
20. According to the MIAS data, a German taxpayer purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, after which he purchased goods worth €43,274 the previous year.
The German tax authority did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions in its 2004 VAT return or in the for 2005.
He also did not explain the value of the initial sales.
Due to these discrepancies, the German FA issued a request for information concerning the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community shipments of goods with a total value of 167,246.083 CZK.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side requested to verify whether the delivery reported by the Czech tax inspector had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech tax administration stated that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company does not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
Documents provided to the NKÚ by the responsible tax official show that on 30 March 2006, together with the Managing Director of the Czech Tax Office, a protocol on the commencement of the VAT audit for the 4th quarter of 2004 and the period January to December 2005 was drawn up.
At the same time, the tax inspector was asked by the tax officer to submit all accounting and tax documents for this period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole Managing Director expired on 16 May 2005 without a new Managing Director being appointed.
Since April 2006, the Czech tax preparer has not filed any sales tax returns.
In the context of the parallel investigation, NKÚ, in cooperation with BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community supplies between the Czech Republic and Germany which were not the subject of a previous exchange of information between the two countries.
The two Court of Auditors exchanged information on the cases examined through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR) which is not domiciled in Germany informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-South) that it wanted to carry out taxable business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive a German USt-IdNr.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the manufacture of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria on behalf, at the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient own production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the contract to a German tax preparer (UDE) based in Germany.
The following diagram shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria for installation on its behalf, at its own risk and on its own account.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- Because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out on his own behalf, at his own risk and for his own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport began, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were supplied to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as a taxable entity in an EC Member State (CR), no exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from the country of residence of the Czech company 19.
Accordingly, the delivery is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) is also based on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The supply of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The supply of the other wind turbines manufactured in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) supplied both intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community supplies from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community supplies in its German tax returns or in its customs declarations to the German CLO.
Consequently, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies in the same way as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NCP found that (UCR) had not notified intra-Community supplies to Austria, but intra-Community supplies to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four financial administrations (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be required, although in this case there is no evidence of tax fraud or tax evasion.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined case designs to show the size of the differences between the VAT declarations and the MIAS data caused by the different legislation in 2004.
The cases examined also show that it takes some time for the tax authorities and the FÄ to apply the new legal provisions:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax preparer reported shipments of goods with a total value of 792.977.452 CZK to a German tax preparer.
In the same period, another Czech tax preparer reported in his ZM intra-Community deliveries to another German tax preparer with a total value of 18,157.265 CZK.
The information provided by the BRH to NKÚ showed that both cases involved electricity supplies.
Both Czech tax authorities took into account the above-mentioned deliveries in their customs documents in accordance with Czech law No. 235 / 2004, which was in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of NKÚ found that in 2004 different legal provisions on the supply and acquisition of electricity between the Czech Republic and Germany applied.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax authorities declared the supplies of electrical energy to be intra-Community supplies in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235 / 2004 in force in 2004, according to the German legal provisions in force in 2004, these were not intra-Community purchases of goods, but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in the legal provisions were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law Nr. 635 / 2004, which changed some tax provisions as of 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax preparer declared intra-Community deliveries in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 to a German tax litigant with a total value of 240.411.163 CZK and another Czech tax litigant declared intra-Community deliveries in his ZM for the same period to another German tax litigant worth 263.470.776 CZK.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that both cases concerned supplies of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law No 235 / 2004 applicable from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy shall be the place where the acquirer has its legal domicile, registered office or place of business for which this delivery is made.
Therefore, the Czech tax authorities should not have specified the electricity supply in their 2005 SDGs.
The fact that both control faculties treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies led to a material difference of 503.881.939 CZK in MIAS.
Final note:
The cooperation has achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both Court of Auditors gained in-depth knowledge of the VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal provisions governing VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions came to light.
Some of these are worth further observation.
On the basis of the results of the audit, both Court of Auditors drew up recommendations on the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a control review should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through cooperation between the two Court of Auditors is the basis for the successful implementation of future audits in the field of VAT administration.
